# Learning How To Learn: What is chunking?

Chunks are pieces of information which are bound together through use and meaning. And correspond to connections between particular groups of neurons.

Our working memory only has about 4 slots in which it can store ideas, which is why you need to repeat a long phone number over and over to keep it in your mind.

As we practice and learn, associations are made between ideas in our mind, slowly forming chunks of understanding or learning. These chunks only take up one slot of working memory, so the bigger the chunks we can create the more complex the problems we can solve in our working memory.

Chunking is essential for being able to deal with increasingly complex ideas, as each chunk takes up only one of the 4 'slots' in your working memory, and allows you to work with 'denser' building blocks of information.


